    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-09-27T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-09-27T13:00:00-05:00" n="355"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d355">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">689.90D/9–1051: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Afghanistan</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-09-27T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 27, 1951—2 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>119. Re <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 139, Sep 10.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d355fn1">Not printed, but see editorial note, <hi rend="italic"
                            >supra.</hi>
                    </note> Assuming <hi rend="italic">Aide-Mémoire</hi> official <gloss
                        target="#t_GOA1">GOA</gloss> position re <gloss target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss>
                    counterproposal Emb in its discretion shld point out to <gloss
                        target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss>:</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>It wld appear from <hi rend="italic">Aide-Mémoire</hi> that US Nov 6
                        proposal can no longer usefully serve as basis for improving Afghan <gloss
                            target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss> relations as both govts concerned have
                        found it impossible agree on all four points US approach. </item>
                    <pb facs="0527" n="1991" xml:id="pg_1991"/>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Both govts however appear have reached agreement on first three points Nov
                        6 approach thus encouraging US hope that they may pursue further bilateral
                        negotiations (such as Shah talks) leading to better understanding between
                        them.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>As it appears Shah talks thoroughly explored possibility of agreement on
                        terms of Nov 6 approach, it wld seem unnecessary for US Govt transmit any
                        further communication from <gloss target="#t_GOA1">GOA</gloss> to <gloss
                            target="#t_GOP1">GOP</gloss> this regard.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Consequently US Govt considers further discussion Nov 6 approach wld serve
                        no useful purpose and considers this approach at an end.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>At same time US sincerely hopes both govts will be able take bilaterally
                        effective measures lessen existing tensions.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Report <gloss target="#t_GOA1">GOA</gloss> reactions soonest.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
